Some String Exercises

Exercise #5
Assign to a variable in your program a triple quoted string that contains your favourite
paragraqph of text, perhaps a poem, a speech, instructions to bake a cake, some inspirational
verse, etc. 

Write a function which removes all punctuation from teh string. Breaks the string into a list of 
words, and counts the number of words in your text that contain the letter "e". Your program should 
print an analysis of the text like this 

"your text contains 243 words, of which 1109 (44%) contain an "e"

my_story = """
So live your life that the fear of death can never enter your heart.Trouble no one about their religion; respect others in their view, and demand that they respect yours.Love your life, perfect your life,
beautify all things in your life.Seek to make your life long and its purpose in the service of your people. When it comes your time to die, be not like those whose hearts are filled with the fear of death, so that when their time comes they weep and pray for a little more time to live their lives over again in a different way.
Sing your death song and die like a hero going home. 

"""

import string





def remove_punct_count( my_story):
    
    count_Words = 0
    count_e = 0
    phrase_without_punctuation = ""			#define an empty string without punctuation
    for letter in my_story:
        if letter not in string.punctuation:
             phrase_without_punctuation += letter	#add the letter to the phrase without punctuation
    phrase_without_punctuation.split()			#split the story into words
    print(phrase_without_punctuation)
    for word in phrase_without_punctuation:
         count_Words += 1
         if "e" in word:
             count_e += 1
    print("your text contains", count_Words, "words, of which ", count_e ,  " contain an e")
    
    
