############ Chap 10 Recursion
first example of recursion ---Drawing Fractals 

Recursion : The ability for a function to call itself in order to solve smaller subproblems
---Defining something in terms of itself 


Fractals example
Now let us think about it the other way around. To draw a Koch fractal of order 3, we can simply draw four order 2
Koch fractals. But each of these in turn needs four order 1 Koch fractals, and each of those in turn needs four order 0
fractals. Ultimately, the only drawing that will take place is at order 0. This is very simple to code up in Python:





def main(): 

    import turtle

    #set up window
    window = turtle.Screen()
    window.bgcolor("lightgreen")
    alex = turtle.Turtle()

    def koch(tortoise, order, size): 

        """
           Make turtle tortoise draw a Koch fractal of 'order' and 'size'
           Leave the turtle facing the same direction
        """

        if order == 0:				# base case
            tortoise.forward(size)
        else: 
            koch(tortoise, order-1, size/3)	#go 1/3 of the way
            tortoise.left(60)
            koch(tortoise, order-1, size/3)	#go 1/3 of the way
            tortoise.right(120)
            koch(tortoise, order-1, size/3)	#go 1/3 of the way
            tortoise.left(60)
            koch(tortoise,order-1, size/3)

    koch(alex, 4, 9)


'''
   as a note when using an IDLE then type the program and to make it work 
   call main afterwards
   also note Koch(tortoise, order, size) works with much larger sizes than order 
'''

main() 


We can tighten up the code by using a loop under the else


def main(): 

    import turtle

    #set up window
    window = turtle.Screen()
    window.bgcolor("lightgreen")
    alex = turtle.Turtle()

    def koch(tortoise, order, size): 

        """
           Make turtle tortoise draw a Koch fractal of 'order' and 'size'
           Leave the turtle facing the same direction
        """

        if order == 0:				# base case
            tortoise.forward(size)
        else: 
           for angle in [60, -120, 60, 0]: 
               koch(tortoise, order-1, size/3)
               tortoise.left(angle)

    koch(alex, 3, 60)



main() 

#high Level view 
def main():
    def factorial(n):
        if n == 0:
            return 1
        else:
            result = n * factorial(n - 1)
            print (result)
            return result
    print(factorial(5))

        
